Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt:
NOT CALLED ON THE RECORD;  
Defendant Elizabeth A Frank in court.  Prosecuting attorney Alyssa M. Schaller in court for the State of Wisconsin. 
Ms Frank filed a petition for appointment of counsel.  She may still qualify for a public defender.  Court give the defendant 2 weeks to reapply with the Public Defenders office for representation.  If Ms. Frank does not qualify, court will use the Petition filed on today's day for a court appointed counsel on the next date.
Hearing scheduled for November 14, 2022 at 09:30 am.

Case called at 8:39 a.m.
Attorney Patrick Campbell in court for State of Wisconsin. 
Defendant Elizabeth A Frank in court.  
Court indicates that the defendant need to go to the Public Defender's office to see if she qualifies for representation.
Hearing scheduled for October 31, 2022 at 08:30 am.

Defendant to comply with I.D. Processing.  Absolute sobriety, defendant is not to possess or consume any alcohol.  Defendant is not to use/possess any controlled substances without a valid prescription and take as prescribed.  Defendant not to possess any drug paraphernalia.  Defendant is not to enter any premises, other than a grocery store, that sells/serves alcohol beverages by the drink or into any liquor store.  Defendant to have no violent contact with Victim A/Victim B listed in the Criminal Complaint/Victim Identification Key.  Defendant is not to share, reproduce or distribute any personal and/or identifying information about the crime victim(s), except to their attorney.

01:03 PM Defendant Elizabeth A Frank appeared by phone means, in custody.   District Attorney's Office Law Intern Niki Kane appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Attorney Amanda Nimmer appears as friend of the court.  Defendant was not evaluated by the public defender's office.  Defense acknowledges receipt of complaint and waives reading of complaint.  Service admitted/advised of charges and potential penalties.  Court advises of right to an attorney.  NOT GUILTY PLEA ENTERED BY COURT.  Hearing scheduled for September 30, 2022 at 08:30 am.
Victim/Witness Identification Key filed, under seal, by the District Attorney's office.
State's Demand for Discovery and Inspection and Notice of Intent to Use Defendant's Statement and DNA Evidence.
